  1. Examine if there is evidence of spatial dependence in a rare and a common species in the BCI tree dataset

Based on the graphs of geographic distance and distance in abundance of individuals of Cassipourea guianensis and Symphonia globulifera below, it appears that rare species are spatially independent and common species are spatially dependent. However, only one species was tested each time. When I reran my code using a different common species and a different rare species, the results suggested that both were spatially independent, and when I ran the code again using a third rare species, the results suggested that its distribution was not spatially independent. Therefore, the evidence suggests that both rare and common species can have spatial dependence, but that spatial dependence can be determined on a species by species basis, and cannot be generalized to all rare or all common species. Mantel test and corellogram support my conclusion based on the graphs of distance in abundance and population size for Cassipourea guianensi and Symphonia globulifera. C. guianensis does not have spatial dependence, while S. globulifera does.

Note renaming the species ids to something a little easier to work with like sp_a, sp_b will make model construction a little less cumbersome

  • Model 1: only include a single species as a predictor variable

  • Model 2: include all of the species as predictor variables

    Model 1, with only one species as a predictor, shows strong spatial correlation. The semivariogram first reaches 1.0 at a distance somewhere between 450 to 500, and there appears to be a nugget at about 0.3. However, Model 2, with all species included as predictors, does not appear to show spatial correlation. Using a different spatial correlation structure might yield different results for model 2. Of note, the semivariogram in model 2 does not appear to fit the data as well as in model 1. While the semivariogram in model 2 did not reach 1, there are data at or slightly above 1, beginning at distance of about 410, and based on visual inspection, there is a nugget at about 0.7.

plot(Variogram(sp_mod1, form = ~x+y))

plot(Variogram(sp_mod2, form = ~x+y))

plot(Variogram(sp_mod2_log, form = ~x+y))

  • Did including the spatial error term have a large impact on the coefficients of the model?

    Yes, including the spatial error term increased the coefficients in both models. The coefficient more than doubled for both spatial structures used in the first model, though there was not a difference between results of models including different spatial structures. In the second model, there was an increase in all models with spatial error terms, but the greatest increase was in the rational model with a nugget.

  • Did including the spatial error terms significantly improve model fit (use function anova to carry out model comparison)?

    Model 1 appeared to be very spatially dependent, while model 2 did not. Using spherical or exponential spatial structuring provided significant improvement to model 1 compared to one with no spatial structuring, though neither spherical or exponential structuring was signifcantly better than the other.

    Model 2 did not appear to be spatially dependent based on visual inspection. I played around with some spatial structures, and while there was statistically significant improvement with spherical or exponential structuring compared to the model with no spatial structure, the improvement was less than that of Model 1, and the results of both spherical and exponential structuring were identical in Model 2. When I mapped out the residuals in model 2, it turned out that they were not normally distributed, which prompted me to log transform the data. This greatly improved the model, though did not change my visual interpretation of spatial dependence within the model. Under the log-transformed model, the original variogram still showed little visual evidence of spatial dependence, though there was statistical evidence that including spatial structuring in the model significantly improved the model. I tried 4 different models; rational, exponential, spherical, and rational with nugget. The best model was one with rational spatial structure with the nugget included.

  • Explain why you did or did not observe a difference in the influence of adding the spatial error term between the two models.

    There was a difference in the influence of adding the spatial error term between the two models. The most likely reason for this is that the species included as predictors have different biology and might each be influenced by different kinds of spatial structuring. For example, it is possible that no single species included lacks spatial dependence. However, the kind of spatial dependence that each one is influenced by might be different. Species that are predators are more likely to be spatially structured by internal factors such as competition, while other species may be structured strongly by environmental factors. Thus, some species could be influenced strongly by induced spatial dependence, while others are autocorrelated. Therefore, our model examining one species as a predictor variable may be more strongly influenced by spatial structuring because it is more likely that only one kind spatial influence is present, which makes it easier to detect, and therefore easier to correct against. In the model with many species, different kinds of spatial influences may be causing an effect, and on top of that, each species included may have a different influence on the likelihood of our response species being present.
